'''Larry Edward Smith''', (born 27 October 1945) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] musician, composer, recording artist, and computer programming expert. He studied Engineering Science at the [[University of Toronto]] where he graduated in 1968 with a Bachelor of Applied Science degree specializing in Aerospace Engineering. In 1970 the 24-year-old Smith decided he preferred music to engineering and joined the Canadian rock band [[Lighthouse (band)|Lighthouse]], a rock group that sold millions of records and earned three [[Juno Award]]s as one of Canada‚Äôs leading pop bands. Smith composed, arranged and sang Old Man from the [[Lighthouse (band)|One Fine Morning]] gold album, as well as composing and co-composing various other songs for the group. Starting out on valve trombone with Lighthouse, he later moved to trumpet, and then to keyboards when [[Paul Hoffert]] left the band. Smith also sang backup vocals on most of the recordings.

For some recent solo recordings see <ref>{{cite web|title=Larry Smith on SoundCloud|url=https://soundcloud.com/larry-smith-319296295}}</ref>

In 1984, Smith moved to [[Israel]], where he started a computer software company, specializing in automatic language translation. He is married and has two children.

