{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}} {{Use Australian English|date=August 2012}} {{Infobox Australian place | type = town | name = Cowabbie | state = nsw | image = CowabbiePresbyterianChurch.jpg | caption = Cowabbie Presbyterian Church | image_alt = | relief = | coordinates = {{coord|34|36|0|S|147|0|36|E|display=inline,title}} | pushpin_map_caption = | pushpin_label_position = | map_alt = | pop = | pop_year = | pop_footnotes = | poprank = | density = | density_footnotes = | established = | established_footnotes = | abolished = | gazetted = | postcode = 2663 | elevation = | elevation_footnotes = | area = | area_footnotes = | timezone = | utc = | timezone-dst = | utc-dst = | dist1 = 504 | dir1 = SW | location1 = Sydney | dist2 = 74 | dir2 = NW | location2 = Wagga Wagga | dist3 = 34 | dir3 = NW | location3 = [[Coolamon, New South Wales|Coolamon]] | lga = [[Coolamon Shire Council]] | seat = | region = | county = [[Bourke County, New South Wales|Bourke]] | division = | stategov = [[Electoral district of Cootamundra|Cootamundra]] | fedgov = [[Division of Riverina|Riverina]] | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | visitation_footnotes = | managing_authorities = | url = | maxtemp = | maxtemp_footnotes = | mintemp = | mintemp_footnotes = | rainfall = | rainfall_footnotes = | near-n = | near-ne = | near-e = | near-se = | near-s = | near-sw = | near-w = | near-nw = | near = | footnotes = }} '''Cowabbie''' is a rural community in the central part of the [[Riverina]] region of [[New South Wales]], Australia. It is situated by road about {{convert|29|km|mi}} south of [[Ardlethan, New South Wales|Ardlethan]] and {{convert|32|km|mi}} north of [[Matong, New South Wales|Matong]] along the [[Wagga Wagga]] road.
The place name ''Cowabbie'' is derived from expression used by the local [[Indigenous Australians|Aboriginals]] for cows when they were first seen in the area by these early inhabitants,<ref>{{NSW GNR|id=JPckFxKmGH|title=Cowabbie|accessdate=}}</ref> and Cowabbie Station is one of the functioning properties in the area.
Cowabbie has a rich [[Presbyterian]] history. The original church - dilapidated but memorialised by the small community surrounding it, was first built by the local Hannah family in 1865 and then transported to its current location by bullock-team in 1926.
